The Americas
------------
[2] Brazil (Ceara)
Date: Fri 5 Jun 2015
Source: G1, Globo [In Portuguese, machine trans., edited]
http://g1.globo.com/ceara/noticia/2015/05/numero-de-casos-de-sarampo-no-ce-em-2015-chega-141-diz-secretaria.html.

The number of measles cases in Ceara this year reached 141, according to the epidemiological bulletin released Fri (29 Jun 2015) by the Department of Health. There have been 8 new cases since last Friday.

Ceara is experiencing a measles outbreak that has lasted 18 months, which is considered an extension of the Pernambuco measles outbreak that occurred in 2013 and 2014. Even with new cases, the incidence of measles is slowing in Ceara. In 2014, the state had recorded 694 cases. The Government of Ceara says it will continue the vaccination campaign against the disease to end the epidemic cycle. For the epidemic to be considered over, there must be 90 days without new cases of measles.

According to the Department of Health of Ceara, most cases occur in the city of Caucaia, Greater Fortaleza. On Saturday (30), the secretariat should have provided vaccination in places such as plazas, schools and supermarkets. The campaign in the city is scheduled from 9h to 17h. People [who should be vaccinated include those] up to 29 years of age or up to 49 years if such person has never received immunization, or have lost their vaccine record.

Ceara must clear cases of measles in 60 days to end the outbreak. Ceara already has 100 confirmed measles cases in 2015, according [to] Sesa Agents [who] go to homes to administer measles vaccine in Fortaleza.

Measles is an acute infectious disease, viral in nature, serious, transmissible and highly contagious, very common in childhood. It is transmitted directly from person to person through secretions expelled when coughing, sneezing, talking or breathing. According to experts, this form of transmission is responsible for the high contagiousness of the disease.

In January 2015, representatives of the World Health Organization (WHO) and the Ministry of Health met in Fortaleza to discuss the number of measles cases in Ceara. According to the Ministry of Health, the state [could reverse] the America's measles-free status if the disease is not contained. "It is a time to focus efforts. Children 6 months to 5 years should be properly [vaccinated," said] Carla Domingues.

Vaccination:
Measles vaccine is effective in about 97 per cent of cases. It should be applied in 2 doses from the 9th month of the child's life. Except for pregnant women and immunosuppressed individuals, adults who have not been vaccinated and have not had the disease in childhood should also get the vaccine. The main form of prevention is vaccination by MMR, available at clinics throughout the year. "If one does not know if he took the MMR vaccine, does not know if he had measles in childhood, and has no proof of vaccination, he should look for a clinic to be vaccinated," says Renata Dias, technical adviser of the Department of Immunization, City Health Department (SMS).

