[3] Chile (vaccination policy)
Date: Sun 31 May 2015
Source: Entorno Inteligente [in Spanish, machine trans., summ., edited]
http://www.entornointeligente.com/articulo/6081243/CHILE-Minsal-indaga-origen-de-contagios-por-sarampion-01062015


Health Ministry investigates origin of measles infections
---------------------------------------------------------
This weekend the Ministry of Health confirmed the detection of 2 cases of measles, a disease that can cause death in extreme cases. The cases are a man (aged 31) hospitalized in a private clinic since Fri 5 Jun 2015, but recovering favorably. "Currently epidemiological research is being undertaken to determine where the infection occurred and the target for vaccination."

Under-secretary of public health, Jaime Burrows said today that the last outbreak in Chile was recorded in 2011, associated with Chileans who had had traveled abroad or foreigners entering the country with the disease. But for more than 20 years there had been no accounts of indigenous cases.

The Health Ministry says there are 250 000 children who are not protected against measles. "Chile is free of indigenous transmission. Outbreaks have occurred [due to] imported virus," said Burrows. The secretary explained that while the disease is eradicated worldwide, there will always be a population susceptible to the virus in Chile of between 12 and 15 per cent. So later in 2015, between October and November, a vaccination campaign against measles will be held. The ministry estimates that the number of children under 6 who are exposed to the disease is 250 000, although the National Plan for Immunization (PNI) against this virus is free to all children a year old, with a 2nd dose in 1st grade, explained Fernando Munoz, the head of PNI, in February to La Tercera.

1 of the reasons that could explain the number of unimmunized people is the increase in [the number of] parents who choose not to vaccinate their children for fear of side effects. In the United States, there is concern that cases of measles will increase from fewer than 200 in 2013 to a record 668 in 2015. Meanwhile, between January and May 2015, Chile recorded 169 infections.

