[4] France (Alsace)
Date: Wed 3 Jun 2015
Source: DNA [in French, machine trans., summ., edited]
http://www.dna.fr/sante/2015/06/03/169-cas-de-rougeole


169 cases of measles have been reported in Alsace since early April 2015. Of these 169 cases, 93 are from the "epicenter" of the outbreak, a school in Logelbach, including parents who have resisted vaccination of their children. Another 10 people were hospitalized last Monday. At Mathias Gruenewald Logelbach school, 1 in 4 students was hit by measles.

At the school near Colmar, the spring break lasted for 3 weeks instead of 2. And 30 children have still not returned, not having been vaccinated against measles. "Only immunized children have returned to school after the closure of 1 week," said the head of Vegas pole (Monitoring and management of health alerts) of the regional health agency (ARS). The 30 children whom their parents refused to vaccinate despite the epidemic are taking courses at home.

The school, a Steiner foundation, is a private institution not under contract with the Ministry of Education. The school doctor says that the school is not obliged to follow the directions issued by the ministry, particularly with regard to vaccination.

In Alsace, the virus remains concentrated in the center of the region. Of the 169 cases reported to the LRA by physicians, 151 were Upper Rhine. "Most cases are concentrated in and around Logelbach Colmar and Ribeauville," said Dr Tariq El Mrini.

10 patients, all from Upper Rhine, had to be hospitalized, [mostly] young adults, aged 20 to 30 years. The last hospitalization occurred no later than Monday at Mulhouse. This time, no deaths have been reported, unlike the epidemic of 2008-2011 that killed 7 people in France (not in Alsace). "Measles is a disease which are considered benign but can escalate with damage to the lungs or liver," as well as [the nervous system], says Dr El Mrini. There is no treatment, "you have to lower the [patient's] temperature and avoid dehydration."

Since the arrival of the virus in early April 2015, "the curve peaks and troughs, with between 10 and 20 cases reported every week," says the doctor. The epidemic follows a steady pace. 30 people are currently infected in Alsace. With a 14-day incubation period, measles patients are contagious for 10 days around the rash characteristic of the disease. Knowing these figures, doctors wait 21 days after the declaration of [the last] case to [declare that] the epidemic is over. The last case in Alsace was announced last Saturday [6 Jun or 30 May 2015?].

ARS and the prefecture of Haut-Rhin [remind the public of] the importance of getting vaccinated and [confirming it was administered customarily] during infancy. "Vaccination, updated with 2 doses , is highly recommended for all persons born after 1980, aged at least 12 months," the prefecture reminded the public yesterday, insisting that "Measles is a disease to be taken seriously."

[byline: Anne-Camille-Beckelyngk]

